trefle.io, plant.id use these api'sPlant.id v3
Documentation for API v2 can be found on our GitHub. Or see overview of changes between versions.

Plant.id is a machine learning-based service to identify indoor plants, wildflowers, trees, grasses, and other plant species from images. Additionally, Plant.id can evaluate the health of plants and detect various diseases, vermins or pests. To use the API you need to get an API key.

To use API from python, use SDK: kindwise API client.

How to use this documentation
This is a description of an important part of the API. The specification of the endpoints is given below. In the right column, you can find example calls of these endpoints (on the right you can toggle between different examples).

View this collection directly on Postman to see endpoints and examples, and you can also try it out (after providing your API key).

More implementation examples can be found on our GitHub.

Download the OpenAPI (YAML) definition of this API.

Authentication
You should provide the Api-Key header with your API key. You can request it in the Admin Panel.

Identification request
There are two methods to create a new identification:

using application/json request - all attributes including images are encoded in json body - see the example

using multipart/form-data request - attributes are sent in text fields; images are sent as files - see the example

Attributes:

images

application/json: a list of strings (required) with one or more images of the plant you want to identify, using either:

image(s) encoded as strings in Base64,

public URL(s) of images

multipart/form-data - all images in file fields (names of file fields are not important)

latitude - float (optional) - geographic coordinate, increases the identification accuracy

longitude - float (optional) - geographic coordinate, increases the identification accuracy

similar_images - boolean (optional) - if true, the model also selects images similar to the provided images for each suggestion

custom_id - integer (optional) - a unique identifier, can be used to access the identification results

datetime - string (optional) - to improve results, e.g. for images taken at different seasons, specify the date when the images were taken in ISO format with variable precision (e.g. 2023-06-22 for days or 2023-06-22T11:28 for minutes)

health - string (optional)

only - response contains only health assessment

auto - the health assessment response is included only if a plant has a harmful or non-harmful condition (see is_harmful). The total credit cost depends on whether health assessment is returned (2 credits) or not (1 credit).

all - response contains both plant species classification and health assessment; for such identification, 2 credits are charged (1 for taxa classification and 1 for health assessment)

disease_level - string - control the specificity of suggestions in the response

all - all classes; default

general - only broad classes, e.g. feeding damage by insects

suggestion_filter - object (optional) in format {"classification": "FILTER_NAME (filter examples below)"} - restricts the output of the model to a specified list of classes (taxonomy, region or plant type) and adjusts the probabilities. The lists can be combined with logical operators and parentheses. The lists are available here. Examples:

Vegetables - {"classification": "vegetable"}

Houseplants and wild plants in Europe - {"classification": "houseplant OR continent__europe"}

Trees in Europe and North America - {"classification": "(continent__northern_america OR continent__europe) AND tree"}

classification_level - string (optional) - classification model can give plant identification at 3 levels of taxonomy: genus, species and infraspecies (includes cultivars, subspecies, varieties and trademarks). This attribute allows to adjust which type of taxon is presented in response.

species - suggested plants are genus and species; default

all - suggested plants are genus, species and infraspecies

genus - suggested plants are only genus

classification_raw - boolean (optional) - if true, suggestions of classification are kept in 3 original taxonomy levels (genus, species and infraspecies), without postprocessing. Please note that the response structure is changed, see the example.

symptoms - boolean (optional) - if true, returns heatmaps (as base64 images) and severity score for each identified disease symptom, and an overall defect score, see the example.

Identification result
Here we comment on important parts of the result. For a complete example of the results see the response examples below.

access_token - a unique identifier of the identification, can be used to access the identification results

result->is_plant - prediction of the model about presence of a plant in the input image; see this collection for examples

binary - if false, image probably does not contain a plant

probability - likelihood that image contains a plant

result->classification->suggestions - predictions of the model containing taxa (genus or species) suggestions and additional information; each suggestion consists of:

id - the id of the suggested taxon, which doesn't change over time

name - the name of the taxon in our database (can change over time)

probability - the level of certainty that suggested taxon is the one in the image

similar_images - if similar_images=true is in request, list of representative images of the identified plant is returned; the images are selected to resemble the input image; they may contain license data that should be cited when using the image

details - additional info you requested, see below

Health assessment result
If you request health assessment (via the health request attribute or the health_assessment endpoint), the response includes health block with a list of suggestions (classes). For a full example of the results, see the response examples below.

result->is_healthy - prediction about whether the plant in the input images is healthy

binary - boolean - true if the images are likely to contain a healthy plant

probability - probability that images contain a healthy plant

result->disease -> suggestions- predictions of the model include disease suggestions or non-harmful classes, and additional information; each suggestion consists of:

id - string - stable identifier of the class (does not change over time)

name - string - name of the class, either a non-scientific name (e.g. water deficiency) or scientific name (e.g. Agrobacterium tumefaciens); may change over time

probability - number (0–1) - model confidence that this class is present in the image

similar_images - if similar_images=true is in request, list of representative images of the identified plant is returned; the images are selected to resemble the input image; they may contain license data that should be cited when using the image

details - additional requested information, see below

result->disease -> question- follow-up questions designed to differentiate between the suggestions of the model (can be null when no question is needed). See this article for details.

text - selected question

options - one of the model's suggestions for yes and no answers (with suggestion_index, entity_id and name referring to the list of disease suggestions)

Details
There is a list of additional information about plant that you can get in identification result. To get specific information, include the detail's name in the GET parameters.

The default language is English; to get details in a different language include the language parameter in the GET parameters. ISO 639 two-letter language codes are used, except for Simplified Chinese (zh) and Traditional Chinese (zh-hant).

If a certain detail is unavailable, null is returned.

Some details are licensed. If you want to use this detail, you should also cite the source.

⚠️ We are not liable for damages or injury caused by actions based on inaccurate, misleading, incomplete or wrong information provided.

This is a basic description of the available details. To see examples of return values and their exact format, see this example (for health assessment) with all details for a single language or this example with multiple languages.

Taxa classification
common_names - list of strings - localized - local, non-scientific name

url - string - localized - link to plant profile page (usually Wikipedia); if localized page not available, an English one is provided

description - string - localized, with license - short description from Wikipedia

description_gpt - string - localized - short description from GPT

description_all - string - localized, some with license - short description, combined Wikipedia and GPT. Read more.

taxonomy - dict - scientific taxonomy

name_authority - string - scientific name of the plant and authority, for example, Taraxacum officinale F.H.Wigg.

rank - string - taxonomic rank

gbif_id - integer - id in GBIF database

inaturalist_id - int - id in iNaturalist database

image - string - with licence - URL of representative image

images - list - with licences - list of more URLs of representative images

synonyms - list - other names of the plant

edible_parts - list - edible/medicinal parts of the plant; read more in the Handbook

propagation_methods - list - propagation methods of the plant (eg. seeds, cuttings...); read more in the Handbook.

watering - dict - minimum and maximum of how wet environment the plant prefers; read more in the Handbook

best_watering - string - short paragraph on optimal watering practices, English only

best_light_condition - string - short paragraph on optimal lighting, English only

best_soil_type - string - short paragraph on optimal soil types for growing the plant, English only

common uses - string - short paragraph on how the plant can be used, English only

toxicity - string - short paragraph on whether the plant is poisonous to humans or animals, English only

cultural_significance - string - short paragraph on the importance of the plant in human culture, English only

gpt - list - categories to which the plant belongs. They can include taxonomy, region or plant type. The lists are available here. Generated by LLM.

Diseases
local_name - string - localized - name of a class in the requested language; typically translations of non-scientific classes, such as water deficiency.

description - string - localized - short description compiled from Wikipedia or drafted with an LLM and reviewed by a plant-health expert

url - string - localized - link to a profile page for the class (usually Wikipedia or iNaturalist); an English page is provided if the requested page is not available; kindwise’s wiki-style knowledge base when Wikipedia coverage is missing

treatment - dict - treatments and prevention for diseases. Not AI-generated but carefully compiled by a domain expert. Biological or chemical treatments for the disease may not be present for all diseases, but prevention is always present. Read more in the Handbook.

biological - string - non-chemical/biocontrol options

chemical - string - chemical controls

prevention - string - cultural practices and preventative measures

is_harmful - boolean - indicates whether a class is non-harmful (e.g., lichen/moss cover, flower buds, harmless insects) (non_harmful)

classification - list - class higher in taxonomic hierarchy; may be empty for non-taxonomic or generalized classes.

common_names - list - common names for the class

The available languages are: English - en, German - de, Czech - cs, Spanish - es, French - fr, Italian - it, Dutch - nl, Polish - pl, Swedish - sv, Simplified Chinese - zh, Traditional Chinese - zh-hant, Danish - da, Turkish - tr, Hindi - hi, Arabic - ar, Brazilian Portuguese - pt-BR, Korean - ko.

Response codes
Response code	Explanation
200	Successful request
201	Identification created
400	Invalid input data - check error message for details
401	Invalid API key
404	Object not found, e.g. identification, conversation
429	Not enough credits
500	Server error, try again or contact support
